60 2021-01-12 muscle pain At 4hrs post vaccination experienced extreme muscular pain between shoulder blades. The following we... Read more
Close
At 4hrs post vaccination experienced extreme muscular pain between shoulder blades. The following week, as far as I can recall, I began to have tingling from the right shoulder blade down to my hand. I thought I may have a pinched nerve and went to the walk in clinic to be seen by the nurse practitioner that is in the same office as my primary. She examined me and thought it sounded like a pinched nerve and said I was swollen in the area of complaint. Cervical and thoracic x rays were taken (normal) and was told to take Flexeril and steroids. Pain was getting worse and primary told me to begin taking Meloxicam and have physical therapy. I have been doing both beginning 1-11-2021. Pain continues with no improvement. Do not know if my symptoms are caused from the Covid shot, but just seemed to me that it was quite a coincidence that muscle pain began on the same day as receiving the shot.

She was counting on feeling better by tomorrow. She further described her achy feeling as her joints are achy including her knees, back and her elbow, but only her right elbow. She received the injection in her left arm. All she wanted to do now, was to crawl into a warm bed. She stated that she was fine after the first shot. Her arm was a little sore and that was it. She had her first COVID-19 Vaccine injection in her left arm. The soreness at the injection site lasted 2 days and then recovered completely. She did not provide her concomitant medications, stating that she took the same medications that she usually took and had not started anything new. She stated that she was 60 and has the what she had, but she did not have anything of concern; further stating that she had no breathing difficulties or anything like that. The patient underwent lab tests and procedures which included body height: 172.72 cm, body temperature: 93, body temperature: 96, all on an unspecified date. The outcome of events was not resolved.

left neck moderate to severe pain; pain started radiating down her left arm and down left leg; weakening her joints on those extremities/ shoulder pain; This is a spontaneous report from a contactable other healthcare professional reporting for herself. A 60-year-old female patient received the first dose of bnt162b2 (BNT162B2, lot number: EK5730, expiry date: unknown), via an unspecified route of administration, on 16Dec220, at a single dose on arm right for COVID-19 immunization. Medical history included diabetes mellitus 2, hypertension (HTN), migraines, back pains, hypothyroidism, and allergies to latex and kiwi. The patient received the vaccine at a military base. She did not receive other vaccines in four weeks. The patient was not pregnant at the time of vaccination. She had no COVID prior vaccination and was not tested for COVID post vaccination. Concomitant medications included unspecified medications; she received other medications in two weeks. The patient previously took gabapentin and topiramate (TOPAMAX), in which she experienced allergies. On the second day after receiving the vaccine, 18Dec2020 04:00 AM, the patient started feeling left neck moderate to severe pain, and the pain started radiating down her left arm and down left leg, weakening her joints on those extremities. This continued severely for 3 days. At this time, she continued to feel mild left neck, shoulder and arm pain intermittently. She could not report this immediately due to not having her vaccine documents which she forgot at her workplace as she proceeded to vacation. She had paused in getting the second dose that was due on 07Jan2021, waiting to hear from Pfizer. The patient received NSAIDS and Muscle relaxant medications as treatment for the reported adverse events. Outcome of the events was recovering.

8.5 hours after vaccine injection, I suddenly began experiencing fatigue and extreme joint and muscle soreness. Initially I noticed my knees hurting with radiating pain up into my thighs. My head hurt, particularly at the back of my skull, near my neck. My neck muscles were sore, as were BOTH shoulders - my right shoulder (injection site) was only slightly sorer than my left shoulder. I called a 24/7 nurse associated with insurance company to ask if ibuprofen or tylenol were acceptable treatments for my symptoms. She told me I could take either and alternate if I felt I needed to maximize relief. I noticed the joins in my toes and fingers were hurting. It was frightening to experience tightness in my chest and back muscles. I never felt like my lungs were compromised, there was just a heaviness as the muscles seemed constricted. I felt a slight rise in my heart rate and experienced a few palpitations mostly because I kept pondering how much worse my symptoms could get. I was a little cold, so I decided to go to bed after drinking extra water (also a suggestion from the nurse). I slept for a few hours 10:00 PM - 4:00 AM then got up and called an advise nurse to report that my joint and muscle pain were not subsiding. She encouraged water and more painkiller. As the day wore on, I felt less achy and more shaky/jittery. My thinking was somewhat unclear - I felt a little dizzy, out of balance, off-kilter and brain "foggy." As I write this 36 hours after my injection, my symptoms are subsiding. Where I felt a little chilled during our cool and rainy afternoon, I now feel a wave of heat sort of traveling through my body. It isn't a fever - just an odd sensation that something is still going on.

I am submitting this as a supplementary report to the report assigned on March 1, 2021. This is day 10 after the vaccine and my mast cell reactivity symptoms have increased by the day--internal and external swelling, flushing, pruritis, wheezing, tightness in chest, as well as pain and pressure in arm pits, groin, and ears. By late afternoon I am severely fatigued, weak, and foggy-headed. These symptoms are consistent with those I experienced during the twenty years when my mast cell disease was unstable. Through identification of my triggers and avoidance of the same, I have been symptom and medication free for the past three years--until taking the Covid-19 vaccine. It appears that the vaccine has reactivated an excessive degranulation response in my mast cells and that response is getting worse as my body responds to the vaccine. I realize that the percentage of persons who suffer from a condition like mine is small, but I would have appreciated having the information that I am submitting to you when I was weighing the pros and cons of vaccination. I know from the twenty years of navigating this disease that there is nothing that can be done at this point other than taking various H1 and H2 blockers. This vaccine appears to be undoing the hard-won level of stability achieved through years of careful lifestyle management.

She said she knew her symptoms were not normal for her, and she went for the whole month of Jan2021 with her symptoms. She said the cramps and muscle spams have not gone away completely. Reported she has a small petechia rash on her lower legs. She said last night she had 2 petechia rashes show up on the lateral side of her right ankle. She said the petechia rash started to burn, and her right leg calf muscle became heavy. She said she could tell her right leg calf muscle was going to start to spasm, so she took some coconut oil and applied the coconut oil to her right leg calf muscle and massaged her right calf muscle. She said she had 2 areas of petechia last night (23Feb2021). She said the first time the petechia was noticed was when she went to the Emergency Room on 06Feb2021. Close
I'm not sure this was from the vaccine, but it seems like the only likely cause: I had Pfizer Shot#2 on 2/23/21. I was feeling great for an entire week. Then, a week after the second shot, I got the worst fatigue I can ever remember, except maybe when I was pregnant, starting the evening of March 1. When I awoke on March 2, my body aches were so intense, I felt like I couldn't move out of bed. Then during the day, I tried to take my usual outdoor walk - usually ~ 5 miles/day. I had to turn around part-way because I was so exhausted and my legs felt both like concrete and like they were quaking from tiredness. Later that afternoon, I fell asleep sitting up in my chair SIX times, even though I almost NEVER take a nap! I kept doubting myself because I haven't read about delayed onset of symptoms, but we don't go anywhere indoors at all except for getting the shot at the pharmacy and an MD clinic appointment now and then. (I did have an annual MD appointment on March 2, so was in the clinic that very day, using all precautions. I don't imagine I could have gotten ill instantly from something at the clinic though?) In ensuing days, I continued to feel super-fatigued, but have had more energy each day, to the point where, now, 6 days later, I feel "almost" like myself. I'm still unsure of walking the full 5 miles without getting too tired, and certain body aches are still hanging on (knee, wrists, fingers), but I'm otherwise feeling good. If I had the symptoms right after the shot, I would have been sure it was from the shot, but since it was delayed a week, I was uneasy and it felt a bit scary because I felt so unlike my healthy, spry, active, motivated self. One other odd thing, that may be totally unrelated, but just in case - on the very day of the second shot, I got a huge stye on my left eye - something I haven't had in decades. It has still not gone away after 2 weeks. Just in case you get other reports, I am letting you know about this as well. The fatigue and body aches sound a lot like what is to be expected after the shot, but I do know there have been some eye-related issues as well.

My second COVID-19 vaccination injection on Friday morning, 2/19/2021 resulted initially (starting on Saturday, the day following the vaccination} in a sore right wrist and a much more painful right arm that steadily grew in intensity and spread rather rapidly into my upper torso. By the following day (Sunday, 2/21) my breasts became very sensitive and I had severe pains across my back. This may or may not have been the beginning of a banding type MS exacerbation, but by Monday, 2/22, it was clear that I was experiencing a full-blown and seriously disabling exacerbation. Both legs experienced the tingling and numbness I have had in a prior exacerbation, and by the time I was able to talk to Dr. (my neurologist) on Monday afternoon (2/22), the numbness had progressed upward into my lower abdomen and I was no longer able to stand at all. It appears highly likely that the MS attack was triggered by the response of my immune system's reacting to the discomfort and severe body pains that occurred following the vaccination. I told Dr. of the total loss of feeling and use of both legs and was experiencing a increasing numbness from toes up to abdomen. Before ordering the high doses of corticosteroids used to stop my exacerbation, Dr. sent me to the Emergency Room for testing to make sure I did not have an infection that could be covered up by the steroids. When this testing did not show any such infection, the ER administered an IV infusion of 1 gram of solumedrol, followed by gradually decreasing high oral doses of prednisone. As of this date, numbness has started decreasing and some limited utility of right leg has returned. Still i can no longer stand and perform even the minimal movements to-and-from wheelchair to bed or toilet without substantial physical help (not needed before this exacerbation) from my sole caregiver, my husband.
